      <section>
        <slide source-label="Section" source-number="1.1">
          <title>Defining a topology</title>
        </slide>
        <slide>
          <definition source-number="1.1.1">
            <statement>
              <p>
  Let <m>X</m> be a set, and let <m>\mc T\subseteq \mc P(X)</m> satisfy
  the following properties.
</p>
              <ol>
                <li>
    <m>\emptyset,X\in\mc T</m>.
  </li>
                <li>
    If <m>\mc U\subseteq\mc T</m>, then <m>\bigcup\mc U\in\mc T</m>.
  </li>
                <li>
    If <m>U,V\in\mc T</m>, then <m>U\cap V\in\mc T</m>.
  </li>
              </ol>
              <p>
  Then <m>\mc T</m> is called a <term>topology</term> on <m>X</m>,
  the pair <m>\tuple{X,\mc T}</m> is called a <term>topological space</term>,
  and elements <m>U\in\mc T</m> are called <term>open sets</term> of the space.
  (Usually <m>\tuple{X,\mc T}</m> is abbreviated to just <m>X</m> when the
  topology is known from context.)
</p>
            </statement>
          </definition>
        </slide>
        <slide>
          <note source-number="1.1.2">
            <statement>
This note should be a slide, but only because
slide=<q>true</q>.
</statement>
          </note>
        </slide>
        <slide>
          <p>But this paragraph is, which is why we include it in a slide.</p>
        </slide>
        <slide>
          <theorem source-number="1.1.4">
            <statement>
              <p>
  Let <m>X</m> be any set. Then the following sets are topologies on <m>X</m>.
</p>
              <ol>
                <li><m>\mc T=\mc P(X)</m> is called the <term>discrete topology</term>.</li>
                <li><m>\mc T=\{\emptyset,X\}</m> is called the <term>indiscrete topology</term>.</li>
              </ol>
            </statement>
          </theorem>
        </slide>
        <slide>
          <proposition source-number="1.1.5">
            <statement>
              <p>
  Let <m>\mc T</m> be a topology, and let <m>\mc U\subseteq\mc T</m> be finite. 
  Then <m>\bigcap\mc U\in\mc T</m>.
</p>
            </statement>
          </proposition>
        </slide>
      </section>
      <section>
        <slide source-label="Section" source-number="1.2">
          <title>More advanced things</title>
        </slide>
        <slide>
          <definition source-number="1.2.1">
            <statement>
              <p>
  Suppose <m>D\subseteq X</m> and <m>\cl D = X</m>.
  Then <m>D</m> is said to be <term>dense</term>
  in <m>X</m>.
</p>
            </statement>
          </definition>
        </slide>
        <slide>
          <theorem source-number="1.2.3">
            <statement>
              <p>
  A subset is dense if and only if it intersects
  every nonempty open set.
</p>
            </statement>
          </theorem>
        </slide>
      </section>
